  "prompt": "Do electrons change energy levels instantaneously?",
  "response": "Electrons do not change energy levels instantaneously in the strictest sense. According to quantum mechanics, when an electron transitions between energy levels in an atom, it absorbs or emits a photon corresponding to the energy difference between the levels. This process occurs very quickly, but not truly instantaneously.\n\nIn practice, the transition times are extremely short\u2014on the order of nanoseconds to femtoseconds. In quantum mechanics, these transitions are often described using time-dependent perturbation theory. While the electron seems to \"jump\" from one energy level to another, the actual process involves intermediate states and is governed by probabilities defined by the rules of quantum mechanics.\n\nSo although it appears almost instantaneous to human perception, there is a finite duration involved in the transition between energy levels.",
